Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – possibly the most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have far-reaching consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the response of the political decision-makers had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and nurtured a lasting sense of discontent among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a variety of clichés as to why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of bipartisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed, who would lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
I've heard the same arguments exactly 25 years ago, when I was the Chairman of the economic advisory board of US President Bill Clinton, and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was the issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country has paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments, when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and refused Volcker a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he strived for deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an Ayn Rand follower.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation in comparison to job opportunities and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US consistently held clearly different, but well-articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell prey to populist delusions).
From my perspective, Democrats are right to worry about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, only when labor markets are tight, marginalized groups are brought into the economy and wage differences are reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a trial for every US central bank chief.
Already, the US is faced with difficult decisions as to what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate for African Americans, which has still not returned to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate increases (and the resulting rise in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of a still stronger and more pervasive mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
Firstly, he supported the deregulation agenda of ex-President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial well-being of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take any action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers worldwide have meanwhile declared this as the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not belong to the mandate of the Fed, but thereby he would be wrong.
It belongs to the Fed's task to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater danger to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
A lack of this kind is the last thing the economy needs right now.
A blatant lack of competition and the absence of adequate regulation already allow for excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators attribute good judgment to Powell for the Fed's reaction to the pandemic.
However, every second-year student would have known that you can't tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argued, Powell doesn't feel particularly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board was marked by a series of misjudgments in the context of monetary policy tightening over the past decade, tracing back to the „Taper Tantrum“ of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not a matter for the central bank, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can choke off growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the latest scandal over trading by senior Fed officials has eroded trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lacking awareness of conflict of interest, including in the administration of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been worrying me for a long time.
After four years of Trump having already weakened trust in US institutions, there is now a genuine risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock market transactions would appear to be unseemly.
The Fed resembles the US Supreme Court in some ways.
This is supposed to be above politics, but at least since Bush v. Gore, we know that this is not the case.
Trump has made this clear for all those who still had doubts.
Even the Fed is supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan, by following their party's deregulation agenda, clearly showed that this doesn't apply to them either.
However, while the central bank board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, the power traditionally lies in the hands of the central bank president – and that's much stronger than it is with the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank president who decides what goes to a vote and which topics are shelved or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just an example of how important it is who is at the top of the table.
The US needs a central bank that really commits to taking care of a stable, fair, efficient, and competition-determined financial sector.
Whoever believes that we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation has already gone too far, lacks insight.
We don't need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a lawyer inclined to Wall Street like Powell.
What's needed is someone with in-depth economic understanding and who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There's certainly a lot of people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already proven their abilities.
Lael Brainard sits already on the central bank board, where she has shown her competence and won the trust of the markets – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chief who preserves continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but shares his economic and social program.
